ydford, Devon, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Tremaine, Cornwall, England":"Tremaine, Cornwall, England","Constantine, Cornwall, England":"Constantine, Cornwall, England"},"en":{"1282–1377":"1282–1377","1284–Male":"1284–Deceased","1296–Female":"1296–Deceased","1314–1354":"1314–1354","1254–1286":"1254–1286","1258–1283":"1258–1283","1286":"1286","1296":"1296","1284":"1284","1283":"1283","1282":"1282","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1314":"1314","1258":"1258","1312":"1312","1377":"1377","1354":"1354","1453":"1453","1254":"1254","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Tremayne, Cornwall, England":"Tremaine, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Lydford, Devon, England":"Lydford, Devon, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Tremaine, Cornwall, England":"Tremaine, Cornwall, England","Constantine, Cornwall, England":"Constantine, Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tremayne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Cornish: variant of   Tremaine  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Tremaine","meanings":["Cornish: habitational name from one or more places in Cornwall named Tremayne (Saint Columb Major, Crowan, Saint Martin in Meneage), Tremaine, or Tremain (Pelynt). The placenames all derive from Middle Cornish <i>tre</i> ‘estate, farmstead’ + <i>men</i> ‘stone’, with the exception of Tremaine, which may have <i>menegh</i>, plural of <i>manach</i> ‘monk’, as the final element."]}]},{"name":"Peter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Wondrous’ or ‘enlightenment’.","2  ♀ ‘Fine jade’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":8,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":33,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":46,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":55,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Peter II Tremayne was born in 1282, in Tremaine, Cornwall, England, his father, Peter Tremayne, was 28 and his moth